\text{6's: }& 60, 61, 62, \ldots, 69\quad\Rightarrow\quad 10\text{ integers}
\end{align*}

Thus, there are $10^5$ ways to choose 5 integers from between 20 and 69, inclusive.  There are $10 \cdot 9 \cdot 8 \cdot 7 \cdot 6$ ways to choose 5 integers with different tens digits.  Therefore, the probability that 5 integers chosen have different tens digits is $\frac{10 \cdot 9 \cdot 8 \cdot 7 \cdot 6}{10^5} = \boxed{\frac{3024}{15625}}.$

