There are 5 tens digits (2, 3, 4, 5, and 6), and there are 10 integers in each set of integers with the same tens digit.  Therefore, there are $\binom{10}{5}$ ways to choose 5 integers with the same tens digit, and there are $\binom{50}{5}$ ways to choose 5 integers from the set of integers from 20 to 69, inclusive.  Therefore, the probability that the 5 integers have different tens digits is \begin{align*}
